11 (4) Violated a provision of ORS 697.642 to 697.702 or a rule the director adopted under ORS
12 697.632;
13 (5) Filed an application for registration that on the date the director issued a registration or
14 on the date the director denied, suspended, conditioned or revoked a registration was incomplete in
15 a material respect or contained a statement that was false or misleading with respect to a material
16 fact in light of the circumstances in which the applicant or [debt management service provider]
17 registrant made the statement;
18 (6) Failed to account to interested persons for money or property the applicant or [debt man-
19 agement service provider] registrant received;
20 (7) Was temporarily or permanently enjoined from engaging in or continuing a conduct or
21 practice involving a debt management service or debt resolution service by a court of competent
22 jurisdiction;
23 (8) Is subject to a director’s order that denied, suspended, conditioned or revoked a registration
24 as a debt management service provider or debt resolution service provider, or a license or regis-
25 tration that the director issued under another provision of law;
26 (9) Is subject to a cease and desist order that the director entered within the previous five years
27 after giving the applicant or [debt management service provider] registrant notice and an opportu-
28 nity for a hearing;
29 (10) Demonstrated negligence or incompetence in performing a debt management service or debt
30 resolution service or an act, the performance of which requires the applicant or [debt management
31 service provider] registrant to obtain a registration or license;
32 (11) Failed to supervise diligently and control an employee’s or agent’s actions related to a debt
33 management service or debt resolution service that the applicant or [debt management service
34 provider] registrant performed;
35 (12) Was convicted of a felony or of a misdemeanor for which an essential element is fraud, ei-
36 ther as an individual that is subject to the requirement to register as a debt management service
37 provider or debt resolution service provider or as a member, partner, officer, director or principal
38 of an applicant or [debt management service provider] registrant;
39 (13) Reduced the amount of the bond required under ORS 697.642 or allowed the bond to lapse;
40 (14) Knowingly made a false entry in a consumer’s record; or
41 (15) Knowingly mutilated, destroyed or otherwise disposed of a consumer’s record unless the
42 record concerns a consumer that no longer receives a debt management service or debt resolution
43 service from the applicant or [debt management service provider] registrant or the record is not
44 subject to the retention requirement set forth in ORS 697.672.
45 SECTION 11. ORS 697.822 is amended to read:
[10]

HB 4141
1 697.822. The remedy provided for in ORS 697.718:
2 (1) Is in addition to and not exclusive of other remedies provided by law.
3 (2) Does not limit a person’s statutory or common-law right to bring an action in any court for
4 an act of a [debt management service provider] registrant, or the right of the state to punish a
5 person for violating a law.
6 SECTION 12. Sections 13 to 17 of this 2026 Act are added to and made a part of ORS
7 697.602 to 697.842.
8 SECTION 13. (1) A debt resolution service provider shall:
9 (a) Deliver or make available to a consumer a copy of any agreement the debt resolution
10 service provider enters into with the consumer. The debt resolution service provider may
11 deliver or make the agreement available electronically with the consumer’s consent. An
12 agreement between a debt resolution service provider and a consumer must:
13 (A) Describe the services that the debt resolution service provider will perform for the
14 consumer;
15 (B) Describe how the debt resolution service provider will calculate fees for debt resol-
16 ution services and list the fees the debt resolution service provider will charge, to the extent
17 that the debt resolution service provider has a current list of fees;
18 (C) Estimate in good faith the amount of time that will be necessary to resolve the
19 consumer’s debts and, if the debt resolution services involve offering a resolution to the
20 consumer’s creditors, estimate in good faith the amount of time within which the debt re-
21 solution service provider will make bona fide offers to the consumer’s creditors;
22 (D) Specify the amount of money, or the percentage of each debt, that a consumer must
23 accumulate before the debt resolution service provider makes a bona fide offer to a creditor
24 to resolve the consumer’s debt;
25 (E) State that debt resolution services might not suit all consumers;
26 (F) State that a failure to make timely payment on a consumer’s debts will likely ad-
27 versely affect the consumer’s creditworthiness, might result in a creditor’s attempt to col-
28 lect the debt by means that include a lawsuit or other legal proceeding and might increase
29 the amount the consumer owes in accrued interest and fees, if a debt resolution service re-
30 lies upon or requires the consumer to not make timely payments to creditors;
31 (G) State that, unless the consumer is insolvent, the consumer might have taxable in-
32 come as the result of a resolution of a debt for less than the full amount of the debt, even
33 if the consumer does not receive money;
34 (H) State that the debt resolution service provider cannot compel a creditor to negotiate
35 a resolution of the consumer’s debt and that the debt resolution service provider cannot
36 guarantee a specific resolution or other result from a debt resolution service;
37 (I) State that resolving a debt by means of a debt resolution service requires the con-
38 sumer to meet regular savings goals;
39 (J) State that the debt resolution service provider does not provide tax, accounting or
40 legal advice to consumers unless the debt resolution service provider has a license required
41 to provide tax, accounting or legal advice;
42 (K) State that the debt resolution service provider does not receive compensation of any
43 kind from creditors and operates as the consumer’s advocate with respect to creditors and
44 the consumer’s debts;
45 (L) State that the debt resolution service provider does not make any payment to a
[11]

HB 4141
1 creditor or other person on the consumer’s behalf;
2 (M) List the debts to which debt resolution services apply under the agreement; and
3 (N) State that the consumer must resolve all disputes with the debt resolution service
4 provider by means of mandatory arbitration, if the agreement requires mandatory arbi-
5 tration.
6 (b) Maintain during ordinary business hours a toll-free telephone number or electronic
7 communication method and a staff that is of adequate capacity to accept communications
8 from a reasonably anticipated number of consumers.
9 (c) Comply with 16 C.F.R. part 255, as in effect on the effective date of this 2026 Act, and
10 with Bulletin 2022-05: Unfair and Deceptive Acts or Practices That Impede Consumer Re-
11 views published by the federal Consumer Financial Protection Bureau.
12 (d) File each year with the Director of the Department of Consumer and Business Ser-
13 vices a written report that lists:
14 (A) The total number of consumers in this state for which the debt resolution service
15 provider provided debt resolution services in the previous 12 months; and
16 (B) The total amount of fees the debt resolution service provider collected from con-
17 sumers in this state during the previous 12 months.
18 (2) A debt resolution service provider may:
19 (a) Request or require that a consumer establish and deposit funds into a dedicated ac-
20 count that a dedicated account service provider administers if:
21 (A) The dedicated account is with an insured institution, as defined in ORS 706.008;
22 (B) The consumer owns the funds in the dedicated account and all interest that accrues
23 on the funds;
24 (C) The debt resolution service provider does not own and is not owned by or under
25 common control with the dedicated account service provider, with “control” for the purpose
26 of this subparagraph meaning having the direct or indirect power to manage the debt resol-
27 ution service provider or the dedicated account service provider by contract or by ownership
28 of more than 20 percent of the ownership interest in the debt resolution service provider or
29 the dedicated account service provider;
30 (D) The dedicated account service provider does not give or accept money or other
31 compensation for referrals of business that involve the debt resolution service provider;
32 (E) The consumer may terminate debt resolution services at any time without penalty
33 by providing notice under section 15 of this 2026 Act, after which the debt resolution service
34 provider must notify the dedicated account service provider of the termination within five
35 business days after receiving the consumer’s notice; and
36 (F) The debt resolution service provider discloses the requirements specified in subpara-
37 graphs (A) to (E) of this paragraph in any agreement with the consumer;
38 (b) Extend credit to a consumer for the purpose of deferring some or all of the
39 consumer’s debts, or negotiate with another person for an extension of credit to the con-
40 sumer, at no additional expense to the consumer, if the person with which the debt resol-
41 ution service provider negotiates the extension of credit has authority or a license necessary
42 to extend credit in this state;
43 (c) Terminate an agreement with a consumer by delivering a written notice of termi-
44 nation electronically or by postal mail:
45 (A) Not later than 60 days after the consumer fails to perform an obligation due under
[12]

HB 4141
1 the terms of the agreement, in which case the consumer does not owe any further payment
2 to the debt resolution service provider as of the date of termination; or
3 (B) Immediately, if the consumer refuses to pay the debt resolution service provider a
4 fee that the debt resolution service provider has earned; and
5 (d) Recover all fees the debt resolution service provider has earned before a consumer
6 terminates an agreement as provided in section 15 of this 2026 Act, if the debt resolution
7 service provider charges and receives the fee in accordance with the agreement and does not
8 violate the provisions of section 14 (1)(a) of this 2026 Act.
9 (3)(a) A fee that a dedicated account service provider charges or collects from a con-
10 sumer or that a person charges or collects from a consumer for legal services is not a fee
11 that a debt resolution service provider charges or collects for a debt resolution service.
12 (b) A debt resolution service provider need not report or account to the director or a
13 consumer for a fee described in paragraph (a) of this subsection.
14 SECTION 14. (1) A debt resolution service provider may not:
15 (a) Request, charge, receive or collect a fee from a consumer unless and until:
16 (A) The debt resolution service provider and the consumer enter into an agreement as
17 provided in section 13 of this 2026 Act and the debt resolution service provider charges the
18 fee in accordance with the terms of the agreement;
19 (B) The debt resolution service provider negotiates, renegotiates, resolves, reduces or
20 otherwise alters the terms of at least one of a consumer’s debts in accordance with the
21 terms of any agreement between the debt resolution service provider and the consumer;
22 (C) The consumer makes at least one payment under the terms of any resolution between
23 the consumer and any creditor that is a party to the resolution; and
24 (D) The debt resolution service provider’s fee either:
25 (i) Bears the same proportional relationship to the total fee the debt resolution service
26 provider charges the consumer for all debt resolution services that the amount of the debt
27 that is negotiated, renegotiated, resolved, reduced or otherwise altered bears to the
28 consumer’s total debt at the time the consumer entered into an agreement with the debt
29 resolution service provider; or
30 (ii) Is a fixed percentage of the amount the consumer saved in debt payments, interest
31 or otherwise as a result of the negotiation, renegotiation, resolution, reduction or alteration
32 of the terms of each of the debts subject to the agreement, measured as the difference be-
33 tween the amount the consumer owed on each debt and the amount the consumer actually
34 paid to satisfy each debt;
35 (b) Require from a consumer, or exercise, a power of attorney that authorizes the debt
36 resolution service provider to enter into a binding agreement to fully discharge a debt in
37 return for a payment of a specific sum of money;
38 (c) Send a creditor a cease and desist notice;
39 (d) Require a consumer to notify a creditor that the consumer’s address or phone num-
40 ber has changed in an attempt to divert communications from the creditor to the debt re-
41 solution service provider instead of to the consumer;
42 (e) Exercise or attempt to exercise any authority on behalf of the consumer after the
43 consumer has terminated an agreement as provided in section 15 of this 2026 Act;
44 (f) Initiate, or request that a dedicated account service provider initiate, a transfer of
45 any money from a consumer’s dedicated account unless the transfer:
[13]

HB 4141
1 (A) Returns money to the consumer;
2 (B) Occurs before any agreement between the debt resolution service provider and the
3 consumer terminates or expires;
4 (C) Is a fee that the debt resolution service provider earns in accordance with paragraph
5 (a) of this subsection; or
6 (D) Funds a negotiated resolution with a creditor and occurs at the consumer’s express
7 direction;
8 (g) Control or receive a consumer’s funds for any purpose other than receiving payment
9 of a fee the debt resolution service provider earns for debt resolution services;
10 (h) Resolve a debt, represent to a consumer that a debt is resolved or advise a consumer
11 to make a payment to a creditor for the purpose of resolving a debt unless, at the time the
12 debt resolution service provider resolves the debt, makes the representation or gives the
13 advice, the creditor confirms that the debt is fully resolved or that a payment will fully re-
14 solve the debt or is part of a payment plan that, upon completion, will fully resolve the debt;
15 (i) Represent that:
16 (A) The debt resolution service provider will provide any money to pay a bill or to prevent
17 a lien or claim from attaching to any of the consumer’s property; or
18 (B) A consumer’s participation in debt resolution services will prevent any litigation,
19 garnishment, attachment, repossession, foreclosure, eviction or loss of employment;
20 (j) Falsely represent, directly or by implication:
21 (A) That the debt resolution service provider can provide legal advice or legal services;
22 or
23 (B) Any material provision of an agreement for debt resolution services or the character
24 or scope of a debt resolution service, including:
25 (i) How much money or what percentage of a debt a consumer might save by using the
26 debt resolution service;
27 (ii) The amount of time in which a consumer will achieve results from the debt resolution
28 service;
29 (iii) How much money or what percentage of each debt the consumer must accumulate
30 before the debt resolution service provider offers or attempts to negotiate, renegotiate, re-
31 solve or otherwise alter the terms of the consumer’s debt;
32 (iv) How using a debt resolution service could or will affect the consumer’s credit score
33 or other measure of creditworthiness or any collection efforts a creditor may pursue;
34 (v) The number or percentage of consumers that successfully resolve debts by using the
35 debt resolution service provider’s services; or
36 (vi) That the debt resolution service provider is a nonprofit entity;
37 (k) Receive a confession of judgment from a consumer or a power of attorney from a
38 consumer to confess judgment against the consumer;
39 (L) Purchase a debt or obligation of the consumer’s or obtain a mortgage or security
40 interest in the consumer’s property in connection with services the debt resolution service
41 provider provides to the consumer;
42 (m) Receive from or on behalf of a consumer a promissory note or other negotiable in-
43 strument other than a check or demand draft or a post-dated check or demand draft;
44 (n) Disclose the consumer’s identity or identifying information or the identity of the
45 consumer’s creditors, except:
[14]

HB 4141
1 (A) As permitted under federal law or by court order;
2 (B) To the Director of the Department of Consumer and Business Services in response
3 to the director’s lawful demand; or
4 (C) To the extent necessary to administer debt resolution services, which may include a
5 disclosure to:
6 (i) A creditor of the consumer; or
7 (ii) A dedicated account service provider;
8 (o) Advertise, announce, broadcast, display, distribute, print, publish or televise a state-
9 ment or representation that is deceptive, false or misleading, either directly or indirectly or
10 through a person that markets debt resolution services on behalf of the debt resolution
11 service provider;
12 (p) Provide any person with anything of value in exchange for favorable treatment in
13 reviews or favorable placement in rankings;
14 (q) Own or operate a website, electronic resource or publication that provides rankings
15 or consumer reviews of the debt resolution service provider, whether directly, indirectly or
16 through an affiliate of the debt resolution service provider; or
17 (r) Make a statement or representation or take an action that is likely to mislead a
18 consumer as to whether reviews the debt resolution service provider uses to advertise debt
19 resolution services accurately reflect all reviews the debt resolution service provider has
20 received.
21 (2) An agreement under section 13 (1)(a) of this 2026 Act may not:
22 (a) Subject the parties to the agreement to, or require the application of, the law of any
23 jurisdiction other than the federal government or this state;
24 (b) Restrict a consumer’s remedies under applicable provisions of ORS 697.602 to 697.842
25 or another law of this state except as provided in the Federal Arbitration Act, 9 U.S.C. 1 et
26 seq., as in effect on the effective date of this 2026 Act; or
27 (c) Limit or release the liability of a party to the agreement for failing to perform the
28 agreement or for violating an applicable provision of ORS 697.602 to 697.842.
29 SECTION 15. (1) A consumer may terminate an agreement with a debt resolution service
30 provider at any time by notifying the debt resolution service provider in writing, or orally
31 by contacting a representative of the debt resolution service provider or by recording an oral
32 message for delivery to the debt resolution service provider.
33 (2) A debt resolution service provider, after receiving a consumer’s notice of termination
34 under subsection (1) of this section, shall:
35 (a) Within two business days after the date of the consumer’s notice, advise the con-
36 sumer of any effect that the termination will have on any resolution agreements that the
37 debt resolution service provider has negotiated or is in the process of negotiating; and
38 (b) Within five business days after the date of the consumer’s notice, notify the dedicated
39 account service provider of the consumer’s termination and request that the dedicated ac-
40 count service provider communicate with the consumer concerning the disposition of any of
41 the consumer’s funds that the dedicated account service provider holds.
42 SECTION 16. (1)(a) While an agreement for debt resolution services remains in effect
43 between a debt resolution service provider and a consumer, the debt resolution service pro-
44 vider shall deliver to the consumer a statement of account:
45 (A) At least once per month; and
[15]

HB 4141
1 (B) Not later than five days after receiving a request for a statement of account from a
2 consumer, except that the debt resolution service provider need not provide more than one
3 statement of account per month in response to a consumer’s request.
4 (b) A debt resolution service provider shall deliver a statement of account to a consumer
5 within five days after an agreement for debt resolution services terminates or expires.
6 (2) A statement of account must:
7 (a) Show the total amount of money a consumer has deposited into the consumer’s ded-
8 icated account as of the date of the statement of account, the total sum of money the con-
9 sumer now has in the dedicated account and all withdrawals from the dedicated account from
10 the date on which the dedicated account was opened;
11 (b) List all creditors with which the consumer has reached a resolution of the consumer’s
12 debt and the date on which the resolution was reached;
13 (c) List each fee and the total of all fees that the debt resolution service provider charged
14 to and collected from the consumer as of the date of the statement of account and ascribe
15 each fee to a specific debt or resolution;
16 (d) List for each debt that the consumer resolved with a creditor by means of a debt
17 resolution service:
18 (A) The amount of each debt on the date on which the debt resolution service provider
19 and the consumer executed an agreement for debt resolution services;
20 (B) The amount of each debt on the date on which the consumer and the creditor agreed
21 to resolve the debt;
22 (C) The total sum that the consumer paid to the creditor to discharge the debt in full
23 and in accordance with a resolution agreement; and
24 (D) The amount that the consumer paid to the debt resolution service provider as a fee
25 to negotiate, renegotiate, resolve, reduce or otherwise alter the terms of the consumer’s
26 debt.
27 (3) A debt resolution service provider delivers a statement of account to a consumer in
28 accordance with subsection (1) of this section if the debt resolution service provider provides
29 or makes available to the consumer the information described in subsection (2) of this sec-
30 tion by means of a website or other electronic means that are continuously accessible to the
31 consumer at any time.
32 SECTION 17. (1)(a) Except as provided in paragraph (b) of this subsection, a debt resol-
33 ution service provider shall provide to a consumer copies of any agreement for debt resol-
34 ution services between the debt resolution service provider and the consumer and any of the
35 records the debt resolution service provider must maintain under ORS 697.672 (2) that per-
36 tain to the consumer:
37 (A) At no charge and within five days after the consumer submits a request for the
38 agreement or records to the debt resolution service provider in writing, orally in person,
39 orally by telephone or by other means the debt resolution service provider maintains for
40 communications with consumers; or
41 (B) Within a reasonable time after receiving a request from a consumer if the debt re-
42 solution service provider receives the request more than 90 days and less than two years
43 after the agreement for debt resolution services terminated or expired.
44 (b) A debt resolution service provider need not respond to a request from a consumer
45 that:
[16]

HB 4141
1 (A) Exceeds a limit of one request per calendar month;
2 (B) The debt resolution service provider reasonably believes the consumer made to har-
3 ass the debt resolution service provider; or
4 (C) A consumer made later than six years after the agreement for debt resolution ser-
5 vices terminated or expired.
6 (2) In addition to, and not in lieu of, the records that a debt resolution service provider
7 must maintain under ORS 697.672, the debt resolution service provider shall maintain the
8 following records for the specified length of time after the date on which the debt resolution
9 service provider created the record:
10 (a) For a period of two years:
11 (A) Each advertisement, brochure, telemarketing script, promotional material and sup-
12 porting data the debt resolution service provider used in marketing debt resolution services;
13 (B) The names and last known addresses of each of the consumers with whom the debt
14 resolution service provider entered into an agreement to provide debt resolution services, the
15 date on which the consumer executed the agreement or received a debt resolution service
16 and the amount the consumer paid for the debt resolution service; and
17 (C) The names of each of the debt resolution service provider’s employees or former
18 employees who had job duties related to selling or soliciting debt resolution services and each
19 fictitious name an employee used, if the debt resolution service provider permits employees
20 to use fictitious names in communications with consumers; and
21 (b) For a period of five years, each signed or otherwise executed agreement with a con-
22 sumer for debt resolution services.
23 SECTION 18. Sections 13 to 17 of this 2026 Act and the amendments to ORS 697.602,
24 697.612, 697.632, 697.642, 697.672, 697.702, 697.707, 697.718, 697.732, 697.752 and 697.822 by
25 sections 1 to 11 of this 2026 Act apply to agreements for debt resolution services that a debt
26 resolution service provider enters into with a consumer on or after the operative date spec-
27 ified in section 19 of this 2026 Act.
28 SECTION 19. (1) Sections 13 to 17 of this 2026 Act and the amendments to ORS 697.602,
29 697.612, 697.632, 697.642, 697.672, 697.702, 697.707, 697.718, 697.732, 697.752 and 697.822 by
30 sections 1 to 11 of this 2026 Act become operative on January 1, 2027.
31 (2) The Director of the Department of Consumer and Business Services may adopt rules
32 and take any other action before the operative date specified in subsection (1) of this section
33 that is necessary to enable the director, on and after the operative date specified in sub-
34 section (1) of this section, to undertake and exercise all of the duties, functions and powers
35 conferred on the director by sections 13 to 17 of this 2026 Act and the amendments to ORS
36 697.602, 697.612, 697.632, 697.642, 697.672, 697.702, 697.707, 697.718, 697.732, 697.752 and 697.822
37 by sections 1 to 11 of this 2026 Act.
38 SECTION 20. This 2026 Act takes effect on the 91st day after the date on which the 2026
39 regular session of the Eighty-third Legislative Assembly adjourns sine die.
